<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1063,1485]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,511,1063,1088]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Monophyly and relationships:</emphasis>
Following 
<bibRefCitation author="Simon" box="[642,801,1063,1088]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" refString="Simon, E. (1901) Histoire naturelle des araignees. Vol. 2. Roret, Paris, 288 pp. [pp. 381 - 668]" type="book chapter" year="1901">
Simon (
<number box="[732,792,1064,1088]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="1901.0">1901</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano" box="[813,984,1063,1088]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1968) Revision de los generos Acragas, Amycus, Encolpius, Hypaeus, Mago y Noegus (Salticidae, Araneae). Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia, Entomology, 2, 267 - 360." type="journal article" year="1968">
Galiano (
<number box="[917,975,1063,1088]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="1968.0">1968</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
recognized the relationship of 
<taxonomicName box="[1335,1428,1064,1087]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Acragas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1335,1428,1064,1087]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Acragas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,238,1100,1123]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amycus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,238,1100,1123]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Amycus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[261,373,1100,1125]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Encolpius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[261,373,1100,1125]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Encolpius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[396,494,1101,1124]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hypaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[396,494,1101,1124]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Hypaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[518,583,1101,1124]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Mago" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[518,583,1101,1124]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Mago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[656,740,1101,1124]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Noegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[656,740,1101,1124]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Noegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on several characters, including a high carapace, pluridentate chelicerae, and the third leg longer than the fourth. The first two of these are seen in other amycoids, but the longer third leg is unique among amycoids and can be considered a synapomorphy. Although it can be reduced or lost in some species, amycines generally have large mastidia on the male chelicerae. Many amycines are translucent, with few scales on the legs. Another common characters is the high clypeus in males.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1063,1485]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">
Monophyly of the amycines was strongly supported by the All Genes analysis (
<figureCitation box="[1087,1168,1279,1304]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 38" captionStartId="16.[151,258,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[167,1421,206,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,191,1868]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 38. Maximum likelikhood phylogenies from Chimera and Non-chimera matrices, combined 5 gene analyses. Numbers show likelihood bootstrap % for Amycoids only; in parenthesis are bootstrap percentages for analysis without Nilakantha and Gypogyna (shown for deep amycoid branches only). Rectangles at nodes indicate bootstrap support in parsimony analysis (filled rectangle at least 75 %; open 50 % to 74 %). Sites partitioned as per PartitionFinder analysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245750/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">
Fig. 
<number box="[1139,1168,1280,1304]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="37.0">37</number>
</figureCitation>
) and separately by 
<number box="[1386,1417,1280,1304]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="28.0">28</number>
S, actin 
<number box="[215,229,1316,1341]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="5.0">5</number>
C, and 
<number box="[316,344,1316,1341]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="16.0">16</number>
SND 
<number box="[405,414,1316,1341]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="1.0">1</number>
genes (
<figureCitation box="[506,688,1316,1341]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 43" captionStartId="18.[151,258,1806,1828]" captionTargetBox="[168,1425,314,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,299,1785]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 43. Maximum likelihood phylogenies from analyses on individual genes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245751/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">
Figs 39, 41, 
<number box="[656,688,1316,1340]" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" value="43.0">43</number>
</figureCitation>
). The molecular phylogeny strongly supports a basal division of amycines into 
<taxonomicName box="[315,427,1351,1376]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Encolpius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[315,427,1351,1376]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Encolpius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the remainder as sister groups. 
<taxonomicName box="[835,919,1353,1376]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Noegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[835,919,1353,1376]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Noegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1072,1353,1376]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hypaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[974,1072,1353,1376]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Hypaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are resolved as sister groups, as expected because of the developed male eyebrows and similar male palps. 
<taxonomicName box="[1004,1097,1388,1411]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Acragas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1004,1097,1388,1411]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Acragas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1154,1241,1388,1411]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Amycus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="25" pageNumber="276" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1154,1241,1388,1411]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="276">Amycus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sister groups by both the molecular phylogeny and morphology, sharing an extremely high clypeus and elongate chelicerae with a modified promarginal tooth.
</paragraph>
